{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"839"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/839"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.28,0.06,0.14,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112582"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/839"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94615"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3583"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48207"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112582"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a drooping right eyelid that developed over the past couple of days. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes complicated by peripheral neuropathy and diabetic nephropathy, obesity (BMI 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E), and dyslipidaemia. His medications include metformin, perindopril, atorvastatin, and semaglutide. He is an ex-smoker with a 20 pack-year history, having quit 15 years ago. He drinks three glasses of wine per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe reports 6 kg weight loss over the past six months since starting semaglutide, but no night sweats, gastrointestinal or respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His right pupil is constricted compared to the left, with right-sided partial ptosis but no anhidrosis. There is no apparent ophthalmoplegia. Sensation and proprioception are preserved. Power is 5/5 in all limbs. Recent HbA1c is 7.8% (4.0-6.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the ptosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic neuropathy","Carcinoma of the lung","Brainstem infarction","Carotid artery dissection","Thyroid mass"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with Horner\u0027s syndrome (ptosis, miosis) with acute onset. The postganglionic sympathetic fibres that innervate the eye travel along the carotid artery, making vascular pathology an important consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid artery dissection\u003C/strong\u003E can compress or disrupt these sympathetic fibres, leading to postganglionic Horner\u0027s syndrome. The absence of anhidrosis suggests a postganglionic lesion, as sympathetic fibres responsible for facial sweating branch off at the superior cervical ganglion. The acute onset in this patient makes carotid pathology the most likely cause requiring urgent investigation. Other symptoms associated with carotid artery dissection include pain and pulsatile tinnitus. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects peripheral and autonomic nerves in a more gradual, bilateral fashion. Diabetes usually results in an isolated oculomotor palsy which spares the pupil, presenting with ophthalmoplegia rather than Horner\u0027s syndrome. Pupillary sparing occurs because the fibres that cause pupil constriction are located superficially on the oculomotor nerve, making them less susceptible to microvascular ischemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the lung\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered in patients with Horner\u0027s syndrome and smoking history. However, several factors make this less likely: the patient quit smoking 15 years ago, the weight loss is explained by semaglutide use, and there are no respiratory symptoms or night sweats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrainstem infarction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with additional neurological signs beyond Horner\u0027s syndrome, such as diplopia, vertigo, ataxia, or contralateral sensory or motor deficits. The isolated nature of the symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid mass\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause Horner\u0027s syndrome through compression of sympathetic nerve fibres, but would typically be palpable on examination and would be unlikely to occur in isolation without local compressive symptoms such as dysphagia or voice changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Postganglionic Horner\u0027s syndrome can be caused by carotid artery dissection or aneurysm affecting sympathetic fibres.","Carotid artery pathology should be considered in patients presenting with acute onset Horner\u0027s syndrome.","The combination of ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis indicates disruption of the sympathetic pathway to the eye."],"references":["Kanagalingam S, Miller NR. Horner syndrome: clinical perspectives. Eye Brain. 2015 Apr 10;7:35-46. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5398733/","Lele S, Derise N, Medlin T, Takalkar A, Nathan CA. Horner Syndrome Secondary to Metastatic Squamous Cell Carcinoma in the Neck: A Case Series. Ear Nose Throat J. 2019 Apr-May;98(4):223-226. doi: 10.1177/0145561319838248. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30922108/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94615"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94615"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T17:03:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T17:04:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"839"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112582"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"posit